          <span class="bg-quick__card-label">A statement on the hand<br><strong>2 carat oval</strong></span>
        </a>
        <a href="/collections/1-5ct-oval-lab-grown-engagement-rings-copy" class="bg-quick__card">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M6 3h12l4 6-10 13L2 9z"/></svg>
          <span class="bg-quick__card-label">The atelier's sweet spot<br><strong>1.5 carat oval</strong></span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-priorities">
      <h2 class="bg-priorities__title">The order of priority</h2>
      <p class="bg-priorities__intro">Choose in this order and the result will be lovely.</p>
      <ol class="bg-priorities__list">
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">1</span> Cut &amp; light performance</li>
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">2</span> Shape</li>
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">3</span> Carat weight</li>
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">4</span> Color</li>
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">5</span> Clarity</li>
        <li class="bg-priorities__item"><span class="bg-priorities__num">6</span> Certification</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">One</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">On the question of “real”</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">
        <p>Yes, lab-grown diamonds are real diamonds — the same chemical structure (a carbon crystal), the same Mohs 10 hardness, the same brilliance and fire as mined stones. The difference is origin, not substance.</p>
        <p>They pass standard diamond testers because they share the same thermal and electrical properties. Specialised laboratory equipment can identify a stone as lab-grown by microscopic growth markers, but it remains a real diamond in every way that matters in your ring.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">Two</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">Choosing the shape</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">
        <p>Shape changes the look more than most expect. Briefly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Oval</strong> — visually generous on the finger; appears larger per carat than the equivalent round.</li>
          <li><strong>Round brilliant</strong> — the classic. Typically the most fire and sparkle of any cut.</li>
          <li><strong>Emerald</strong> — architectural, with a hall-of-mirrors quality; reveals clarity, so favour cleaner stones.</li>
          <li><strong>Cushion</strong> — soft, romantic, often strong value next to round.</li>
          <li><strong>Princess</strong> — modern, sharply rectilinear, plenty of sparkle.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bg-tip">For maximum visual size relative to price, an oval is hard to beat.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">Three</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">Cut — the single thing that matters most</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">
        <p>Cut is the largest determinant of how a stone catches the light. A larger diamond cut poorly can read dull; a smaller diamond cut beautifully will read across the room.</p>
        <p>For round brilliants, look for an Excellent or Ideal cut grade. For fancy shapes — oval, cushion, emerald — a single cut grade is less reliable than judging the proportions and light return directly. The atelier compares stones in person to find the one that performs.</p>
        <div class="bg-tip">Put the savings from lab-grown into cut grade. Going from Very Good to Excellent transforms the stone.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">Four</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">Carat — what the sweet spots look like</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">
        <p>Carat is mass, not size. Still, it is the strongest signal of presence on the hand.</p>
        <table class="bg-spec-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Carat</th><th>Reads as</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1.0 – 1.25 ct</td><td>Classic, restrained</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.5 ct</td><td>Noticeably premium — the atelier sweet spot</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.0 ct</td><td>A statement on the hand</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="bg-tip">Want balance? <a href="/collections/1-5ct-oval-lab-grown-engagement-rings-copy">Browse 1.5 ct oval</a>. Want presence? <a href="/collections/2ct-oval-lab-grown-engagement-rings">Browse 2 ct oval</a>.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">Five</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">Color &amp; clarity — where to spend, where not to</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">

        <p><strong>Clarity.</strong> What matters here is whether the stone is “eye-clean” — inclusions invisible to the unaided eye. Beyond that, you are paying for grades only a microscope can see.</p>
        <table class="bg-spec-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Grade</th><th>How we read it</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>VS1 – VS2</td><td>The atelier's value sweet spot. Typically eye-clean across all shapes.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SI1</td><td>Workable — confirm with the atelier that it is eye-clean before committing.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>VVS1 – VVS2 / IF / FL</td><td>Premium grades; appropriate when clarity is a personal priority.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="bg-tip">Emerald cuts show inclusions more readily than other shapes — favour VS2 or better when the cut reveals the table.</div>

        <p><strong>Color.</strong> Where the stone falls on the D–Z scale of whiteness.</p>
        <table class="bg-spec-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Grade</th><th>How we read it</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>G – H</td><td>Bright white in nearly every setting. Strong value.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>D – F</td><td>Premium colorless. The most exacting choice.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="bg-tip">Yellow and rose gold settings can carry slightly warmer color grades comfortably — a useful lever if budget is tight.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-section">
      <span class="bg-section__num">Six</span>
      <h2 class="bg-section__title">Certification — non-negotiable</h2>
      <div class="bg-section__body">
        <p>Always insist on an independent certificate. It is your proof that the stone is the stone.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>IGI</strong> — the most common laboratory for lab-grown diamonds.</li>
          <li><strong>GIA</strong> — the heritage authority, also grading lab-grown.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If a stone arrives without one of these certificates, walk away. Every Laura Milman centre stone ships with one.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-rec">
      <h2 class="bg-rec__title">The atelier recommends</h2>
      <div class="bg-rec__specs">
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">Oval or cushion</span>
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">1.5 – 2.0 ct</span>
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">G – H color</span>
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">VS1 – VS2 clarity</span>
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">Excellent cut</span>
        <span class="bg-rec__tag">IGI or GIA</span>
      </div>
      <p class="bg-rec__note">A balanced specification — substantial presence, exceptional clarity for the eye, full whiteness in nearly every metal, with the cut doing the heavy lifting.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-faq">
      <h2 class="bg-faq__title">Common questions</h2>

      <div class="bg-faq__item">
        <p class="bg-faq__q">What size do most buyers choose?</p>
        <p class="bg-faq__a">1.5 to 2.0 carats is the most common range — lab-grown pricing makes a 2 ct centre stone attainable without the markup of an equivalent mined diamond.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-faq__item">
        <p class="bg-faq__q">Do diamonds hold their value?</p>
        <p class="bg-faq__a">Most diamonds — lab-grown or mined — resell for less than their purchase price. An engagement ring is best chosen for beauty and meaning, not as an investment vehicle. The honest framing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-faq__item">
        <p class="bg-faq__q">Oval or round?</p>
        <p class="bg-faq__a">Round is the classic for sparkle. Oval reads larger per carat and flatters the finger. Neither is more “correct” — it comes to which look you prefer.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-faq__item">
        <p class="bg-faq__q">What setting feels most timeless?</p>
        <p class="bg-faq__a">The Solitaire is the definition of timeless. The Hidden Halo adds quiet sparkle without changing the top-down line of the ring — a worthy middle ground.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

